  "prompt": "I wanted to be an IAS and love History subject but in 12 I've taken PCM. What subject should I adopt after the 12 board to become an IAS?",
  "response": "To become an Indian Administrative Service (IAS) officer, you need to clear the Civil Services Examination conducted by the Union Public Service Commission (UPSC). The choice of subjects for your undergraduate studies is flexible, and you can pursue any discipline you are interested in. Since you love history, here\u2019s how you can proceed:\n\n1. **Graduate Degree:** Choose a graduation subject that aligns with your interests and strengths. Some popular options for aspirants include History, Political Science, Sociology, or even subjects like Geography if they interest you. Even though you are from a PCM background, you can select a subject like History if you are passionate about it.\n\n2. **Optional Subject for IAS Exam:** During the IAS examination, you will need to choose optional subjects for the Mains exam. History is a popular choice among aspirants, especially if you have a strong interest in it. You can start preparing for it early on in your graduation studies.\n\n3. **Preparation Strategy:** \n   - Begin with NCERT books related to history for understanding the basics.\n   - Refer to standard history books for deeper knowledge and exam preparation (e.g., Bippin Chandra for Modern History).\n   - Make notes, focus on the events, their significance, and interconnections.\n\n4. **Other Relevant Studies:** Besides core subjects, it\u2019s helpful to study subjects that will aid in General Studies papers, such as Current Affairs, Polity, and Economics, which can be pursued alongside your major subject.\n\n5. **Coaching and Self-Study:** Consider joining a coaching institute or starting self-study with the right resources and materials, particularly for the IAS Prelims and Mains.\n\n6. **Stay Updated:** Keep abreast of current affairs, as they are crucial for both the Preliminary and Mains exams.\n\nUltimately, choose a subject that you are passionate about and that fits your preparation strategy for the IAS exam. Your career goal is achievable with the right approach and dedication!",
